# Databricks Deploy Pipeline

Use this when the user says "deploy", "redeploy", or "push to production".

## Learnings (for agents)

- **Deployment machine is Databricks.** The app runs on Databricks Apps; there is no separate "Hertz laptop" deploy. Code flows: local → `git push origin main` → **Databricks workspace repo** (Git clone in workspace) → **apps deploy** (builds and runs from that folder).
- **This repo** (`Prototype-LMS-Databricks`) is the canonical Git repo. Push to `origin main` (e.g. GitHub). The workspace path `/Workspace/Users/nh136948@hertz.net/Prototype-LMS-Databricks` is a **Databricks Repo** linked to the same GitHub repo; it does not auto-pull. You must run **repos update** to pull the latest commit into the workspace, then **apps deploy** so the app runs from the updated code.
- **Profile:** Use `-p DanSiaoAuth` (or the user's configured profile) for all `databricks` CLI commands.
- **Lakebase migrations and GRANTs** cannot be run from the CLI unless `psql` is installed locally. Use the **Lakebase SQL Editor** in the Databricks UI (Lakebase project `lms-leo`, branch `production`) to run `docs/lakebase-migrations/*.sql`. After adding tables or columns, re-run GRANTs for the app's client ID (see Step 5b below). If `psql` is on PATH: `databricks psql --project lms-leo --branch production -p DanSiaoAuth -- -f docs/lakebase-migrations/004_add_lead_columns_and_grants.sql`.

## Pipeline overview
0. **Deploy guard** — abort if another deploy is already in progress
1. Pre-deploy validation (testing rule)
2. Merge feature branch into `main`, push
3. Pull latest into Databricks workspace repo (repos update)
4. Deploy app (apps deploy)
5. Post-deploy: verify app; run migrations/GRANTs in Lakebase if needed

