## Step 0 — Deploy guard (MANDATORY)

Before doing anything else, check whether a deploy is already in progress:
```powershell
databricks apps get hertz-leo-leadsmgmtsystem -p DanSiaoAuth --output json
```
Parse the JSON output and check `active_deployment.status.state`.

| State | Action |
|-------|--------|
| `IN_PROGRESS` or `PENDING` | **STOP.** Tell the user: "A deployment is already in progress. Your changes have been committed and pushed to your feature branch but deployment is deferred until the current one finishes." Do NOT proceed. |
| `SUCCEEDED` or `FAILED` | Safe to proceed with the deploy pipeline. |

**If you cannot determine the state** (e.g. CLI error, auth failure), **do NOT deploy**. Report the error and stop.

## Step 1 — Pre-deploy validation
Follow the `pre-deploy-check` rule. Run ReadLints on all changed files. Stop if critical issues found.

## Step 2 — Merge feature branch into `main` and push

Agents work on **feature branches** (see `git-workflow` rule). At deploy time, merge into `main`:
```powershell
git checkout main
git pull origin main
git merge <your-feature-branch> --no-edit
git push origin main
```
If the merge has conflicts, **do NOT force-push**. Report the conflicts to the user and stop.

After pushing, delete the merged feature branch:
```powershell
git branch -d <your-feature-branch>
git push origin --delete <your-feature-branch>
```

## Step 3 — Pull latest into Databricks workspace repo
Pull the latest commit from GitHub into the workspace repo (so the app deploy uses up-to-date code):
```powershell
databricks repos update 2730039622390114 --branch main -p DanSiaoAuth
```
Verify sync:
```powershell
databricks repos get 2730039622390114 -p DanSiaoAuth
```
Confirm `head_commit_id` matches the commit you just pushed.

## Step 4 — Deploy app
```powershell
databricks apps deploy hertz-leo-leadsmgmtsystem --source-code-path "/Workspace/Users/nh136948@hertz.net/Prototype-LMS-Databricks" -p DanSiaoAuth
```
This triggers Databricks to: install npm deps, install pip deps, run `npm run build`, then start uvicorn.
Wait for deployment to complete (default timeout 20m). Source path must be the **full workspace path** (including `/Workspace/`).

## Step 5 — Post-deploy verification
```powershell
databricks apps get hertz-leo-leadsmgmtsystem -p DanSiaoAuth
```
- Confirm `app_status.state` = `RUNNING`
- Confirm `active_deployment.status.state` = `SUCCEEDED`
- Report the app URL to the user

### Step 5b — Lakebase migrations and GRANTs (when schema changed)
If you added or changed tables/columns (e.g. new migration in `docs/lakebase-migrations/`):
1. Open **Lakebase** in Databricks UI → project `lms-leo`, branch `production` → **SQL Editor**.
2. Run the migration script (e.g. `004_add_lead_columns.sql` or `004_add_lead_columns_and_grants.sql`).
3. Re-GRANT so the app can access objects:  
   `GRANT USAGE ON SCHEMA public TO "<APP_CLIENT_ID>";`  
   `GRANT SELECT, INSERT, UPDATE, DELETE ON ALL TABLES IN SCHEMA public TO "<APP_CLIENT_ID>";`  
   Get `<APP_CLIENT_ID>` from `databricks apps get hertz-leo-leadsmgmtsystem -p DanSiaoAuth` (e.g. `service_principal_client_id` or the Lakebase role name used by the app).

## On failure — check app logs
If deploy fails or `active_deployment.status.state` is not `SUCCEEDED`, immediately pull the app logs:
```powershell
databricks apps logs hertz-leo-leadsmgmtsystem --profile DanSiaoAuth --tail-lines 200
```
- Look for `[APP]` lines with Python tracebacks or startup errors
- Look for `[SYSTEM]` lines with build failures (npm/pip install, vite build)
- Use `--search "ERROR"` to filter:
  ```powershell
  databricks apps logs hertz-leo-leadsmgmtsystem --profile DanSiaoAuth --tail-lines 500 --search "ERROR"
  ```
- To stream logs in real time during a deploy:
  ```powershell
  databricks apps logs hertz-leo-leadsmgmtsystem --profile DanSiaoAuth --follow
  ```

Report the relevant error lines to the user before attempting a fix.

## Rollback
The previous deployment remains active until the new one succeeds.
